1. Introduction

This proyect is part of the Kaggle competition House Prices - Advanced Regression Techniques. Our task is to predict the price of a set of houses from the Ames Housing dataset compiled by Dean De Cock.

1.1 Datasets and features

In this proyect we use two datasets:

  • train.csv: It is a set with 1460 houses, 79 features and sale price for each house.
  • test.csv: It is a set with 1459 houses and the same 79 features as in the previous dataset.

1.2 Methodology

As our datasets have a huge number of features, we will perform feature selection. To do so, we will use statistical methods and also machine learning methods. We will also check for normality, homoscedasticity and linearity in numerical features beafore applying a predictive machine learning model. Finally, we will use a regulariced linear regression model to make our predictions.

def general_info(data, title: str, cols_disp=10, max_cols=100):
    print(title)
    print('-----------------------------------------------')
    
    # Shape, duplicates and null values
    print('Shape:', data.shape)
    print('Duplicates:', sum(data.duplicated()))
    print('Null values:', sum(data.isnull().sum()))
    
    # Name of columns
    print('\nColumns:')
    i_0 = 0
    for i in range(len(data.columns)):
        
        if (i % cols_disp == 0) & (i != 0):
            i_cols = data.columns[i_0:i]
            print(f"{i_0}-{i}:", ', '.join([feature for feature in i_cols]))
            i_0 = i
            
        elif (i == len(data.columns) - 1) or (i >= max_cols):
            i_cols = data.columns[i_0 :]
            print(f"{i_0}-{i}:", ', '.join([feature for feature in i_cols]))
            break
            
        else:
            continue
    
    # Number of categorical features
    numerical_features = data.dtypes != 'object'
    print('\nNumerical features:', numerical_features.sum())
    print('Categorical features:', data.shape[1] - numerical_features.sum())

    # Additional features info
    print('\n Data info:')
    print(data.info())

def missing_data(df):
    '''Create a dataframe with information on missing data'''
    # NaN values
    na = df.isna().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    na_percent = (df.isna().sum()/df.isna().count()).sort_values(ascending=False)

    # Null values
    null = df.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)
    null_percent = (df.isnull().sum()/df.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending=False)

    # Concatenate results
    missing = pd.concat([na, na_percent, null, null_percent], axis=1, 
                        keys=['Total_NaN', 'Percent_NaN', 'Total_null', 'Percent_null'])
    return missing


def prepare_inputs(X_train, X_test=False):
    '''Performs ordinal encoding for categorical data'''
    oe = OrdinalEncoder()
    oe.fit(X_train)
    if X_test:
        X_train_enc = oe.transform(X_train)
        X_test_enc = oe.transform(X_test)
        return X_train_enc, X_test_enc
    else:
        X_train_enc = oe.transform(X_train)
        return X_train_enc
    
def DT_feature_importance(model, X, y, ax, features, title):
    '''This function returns a barplot with the importance of 
    the different features used in a Decission tree based ML model'''

    # train the model
    model.fit(X, y)

    # Get importance values
    importance = model.feature_importances_

    # Create dataframe with the importance information
    importance = pd.DataFrame(data=importance, index=list(X.columns), columns=['importance'])

    # Plot
    ax.bar(importance.index, importance['importance'])
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.set_xticklabels(features, rotation=90);


def hist_normal(data):
    ''' This function plots a histogram with the variable distribution
    and superpose it with a normal probability function with the same 
    mean and standard deviation than the data'''

    # Fit normal distribution parameters mean and standard deviation to the data:
    mu, std = stats.norm.fit(data)

    # Plot the histogram.
    fig = plt.figure()
    sns.distplot(data, color='tab:blue')

    # Plot the PDF.
    xmin, xmax = plt.xlim()
    x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)
    p = stats.norm.pdf(x, mu, std)

    plt.plot(x, p, 'k', linewidth=2)

2.4.2 Categorical features selection

We will use the f-test to analyse the relation between our categorical values and the numerical value 'SalePrice'.

To apply the f-test we need to encode our categorical variables and there can not be any missing values.

In[24]:
# List with categorical features
corr_cols = list(corrmat.columns)
all_columns = list(train.columns)
cat_cols = [ele for ele in all_columns if ele not in corr_cols]

# Dataset with categorical features
train_cat = train[cat_cols]

# Ensure datatypes
train_cat = train_cat.astype(str)

# Ordinal encoding
train_cat_enc = prepare_inputs(train_cat)

# Compute f-test por feature-SalePrice pairs
f_test_values = []
for i in range(len(train_cat.columns)):
    f, _ = f_classif(train['SalePrice'].values.reshape(-1, 1), train_cat_enc[:, i])
    f_test_values.append(float(f))

# Create dataframe with f-test scores
f_test = pd.DataFrame({'feature':train_cat.columns, 'f-test (SalePrice)': f_test_values})
f_test.drop(index=37, inplace=True)

# Plot results
sns.barplot(data=f_test, y='f-test (SalePrice)', x='feature', color='tab:blue')
plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=10)
plt.title('Sale price F-test score');

We keep the features with the higher f-test values

In[25]:
cat_cols = ['ExterQual', 'BsmtQual', 'KitchenQual', 'GarageFinish']

2.4.3 Numerical and categorical feature importance

In this section we compare the importance given by different ML models to all the selected features.

In[26]:
# Keep only features selected
selected_cols = num_cols + cat_cols
df_train = train[selected_cols]

# Separate X and y
y = df_train['SalePrice']
X = df_train.drop('SalePrice', axis=1)

# Ordinal encoding specifying categories order
X_enc = X.copy()
oe = OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['NA','Po','Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['Po','Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['NA', 'Unf', 'RFn', 'Fin']])
X_enc[['ExterQual', 'BsmtQual', 'KitchenQual', 'GarageFinish']] = oe.fit_transform(X_enc[['ExterQual', 'BsmtQual', 'KitchenQual', 'GarageFinish']])
In[27]:
# Create subplot figure
fig, axis = plt.subplots(2, 2, sharex=True, figsize=[12,8])
fig.suptitle('Models feature importance')

# Choose models to be used
models = [DecisionTreeRegressor(), RandomForestRegressor(), XGBRegressor()]
titles = ['DecisionTreeRegressor', 'RandomForestRegressor', 'XGBRegressor']
ax = [axis[0, 0], axis[1,0], axis[0,1]]

# Represent feature importance
for i in range(3):
    DT_feature_importance(models[i], X_enc, y, ax[i], features=cols, title=titles[i])

## Feature importance in a liner regression model
# Create and fit the model
model_LR = LinearRegression()
model_LR.fit(X_enc, y)

# Get importance values (these will be the coefficients)
importance = model_LR.coef_

2.6 Normality, Homoscedasticity and linearity

2.6.1 Normality

We want our data to have a normal gaussian distribution

We start with sale price

In[33]:
var='SalePrice'
# Plot variable distribution compared to normal distribution
hist_normal(df_train[var])

# Normal probability plot
fig = plt.figure()
stats.probplot(df_train[var], plot=plt);

Sale price has not a normal distribution. It shows 'peakedness', positive skewness and does not follow the diagonal line.

We will try performing a logarithmic transformation

In[34]:
# Logarithmic transformation
df_train[var] = np.log(df_train[var])

# Plot variable distribution compared to normal distribution
hist_normal(df_train[var])

# Normal probability plot
fig = plt.figure()
stats.probplot(df_train[var], plot=plt);

Now it fits the normal distribution.

We continue with Ground living area.

This distribution is different than the previous ones. In general it presents skewedness, and we see a large number of cero values which refer to houses without basement.

We can not perform logarithmic transformation to values equal cero. To solve this, we will create a variable which accounts for no basement. This way we will not loose this information. And then we will perform the logarithmic transformation to values different from cero.

2.6.2 Homoscedasticity

In this section we look for dependent variables to exhibit equal levels of variance across the range of predictor variable. This is necessary if we want the error term to be the same across all values of the independent variables.

In[39]:
sns.scatterplot(data=df_train, x='GrLivArea', y='SalePrice');

We see that after the logarithmic transformation this scatter plot does not show a conic shape anymore. Having a conic (or diamond) shape would mean lack of homoscedasticity.

Now we check 'TotalBsmtSF' and 'SalePrice'.

In[40]:
sns.scatterplot(x=df_train[df_train['TotalBsmtSF']>0]['TotalBsmtSF'], y=df_train[df_train['TotalBsmtSF']>0]['SalePrice']);

In general 'SalePrice' shows the same level of variance across the range of 'TotalBsmtSF'.

3. Predictive model: Linear regression

We create a predictive model based on linear regression.

We encode categorical features and usea k-fold cross validation to tune two parameters: polynomial degree of the features and regularization parameter.

In[41]:
# Ordinal encoding
df_train_enc = df_train.copy()
oe = OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['NA','Po','Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['Po','Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['NA', 'Unf', 'RFn', 'Fin']])
df_train_enc[['ExterQual', 'BsmtQual', 'KitchenQual', 'GarageFinish']] = oe.fit_transform(df_train_enc[['ExterQual', 'BsmtQual', 'KitchenQual', 'GarageFinish']])

# Separate X and y
y = df_train_enc['SalePrice']
X = df_train_enc.drop('SalePrice', axis=1)

# prepare cross-validation
kfold = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

# Iterate for different features polynomial degrees
MSE_train_list = []
MSE_cv_list = []

max_deg = 3
for degree in range(1, max_deg + 1):

    # Apply model with k-fold cross-validation
    mse_train_klist = []
    mse_cv_klist = []

    for i, (id_train, cv) in enumerate(kfold.split(df_train_enc)):
    
        # Define datasets
        X_train = X.iloc[id_train]
        y_train = y.iloc[id_train]
        assert X_train.shape[0] == y_train.shape[0]

        X_cv = X.iloc[cv]
        y_cv = y.iloc[cv]
        assert X_cv.shape[0] == y_cv.shape[0]


        # Add polinomial features
        poly= PolynomialFeatures(degree, include_bias=False)
        X_train_mapped = poly.fit_transform(X_train)
        X_cv_mapped = poly.fit_transform(X_cv)

        # Feature scaling
        scaler = StandardScaler()
        X_train_mapped_sc = scaler.fit_transform(X_train_mapped)
        X_cv_mapped_sc = scaler.transform(X_cv_mapped)  

        # Apply the model
        model = Ridge(alpha=0.01)
        model.fit(X_train_mapped_sc, y_train)

        # Calculate predictions
        y_train_p = model.predict(X_train_mapped_sc)
        y_cv_p = model.predict(X_cv_mapped_sc)

        # Calculate MSE
        mse_train = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_p) / 2
        mse_cv = mean_squared_error(y_cv, y_cv_p) / 2

        # Save MSE results
        mse_train_klist.append(mse_train)
        mse_cv_klist.append(mse_cv)


    # Mean MSE_train and MSE_cv folds
    MSE_train = np.mean(mse_train_klist)
    MSE_cv = np.mean(mse_cv_klist)
    MSE_train_list.append(MSE_train)
    MSE_cv_list.append(MSE_cv)

    # Std of MSE's
    MSE_train_std = np.std(mse_train_klist)
    MSE_cv_std = np.std(mse_train_klist)

    print('\nPolynomial degree:', degree)
    print('=========================')
    print('MSE_train: %.4f, MSE_train_std: %.4f' % (MSE_train, MSE_train_std))
    print('MSE_cv: %.4f, MSE_cv_std: %.4f' % (MSE_cv,  MSE_cv_std))

# Plot results
plt.plot(range(1, max_deg + 1), MSE_train_list, label='Train')
plt.plot(range(1, max_deg + 1), MSE_cv_list, label='Validation')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel('Polynomial degree')
plt.ylabel('MSE')
plt.title('Lineal Regression Model: Polynomial degree')

Polynomial degree: 1

MSE_cv: 0.0118, MSE_cv_std: 0.0002

Polynomial degree: 2

In[42]:
degree = 2

# Iterate for different regulariztion parameters "alpha"
MSE_train_list = []
MSE_cv_list = []

alpha_list = [0, 0.005, 0.01, 0.015, 0.03, 0.06, 0.1]

for alpha in alpha_list:

    # Apply model with k-fold cross-validation
    mse_train_klist = []
    mse_cv_klist = []

    for i, (id_train, cv) in enumerate(kfold.split(df_train_enc)):
    
        # Define datasets
        X_train = X.iloc[id_train]
        y_train = y.iloc[id_train]
        assert X_train.shape[0] == y_train.shape[0]

        X_cv = X.iloc[cv]
        y_cv = y.iloc[cv]
        assert X_cv.shape[0] == y_cv.shape[0]


        # Add polinomial features
        poly= PolynomialFeatures(degree, include_bias=False)
        X_train_mapped = poly.fit_transform(X_train)
        X_cv_mapped = poly.fit_transform(X_cv)

        # Feature scaling
        scaler = StandardScaler()
        X_train_mapped_sc = scaler.fit_transform(X_train_mapped)
        X_cv_mapped_sc = scaler.transform(X_cv_mapped)  

        # Apply the model
        model = Ridge(alpha=alpha)
        model.fit(X_train_mapped_sc, y_train)

        # Calculate predictions
        y_train_p = model.predict(X_train_mapped_sc)
        y_cv_p = model.predict(X_cv_mapped_sc)

        # Calculate MSE
        mse_train = mean_squared_error(y_train, y_train_p) / 2
        mse_cv = mean_squared_error(y_cv, y_cv_p) / 2

        # Save MSE results
        mse_train_klist.append(mse_train)
        mse_cv_klist.append(mse_cv)

    # Mean MSE_train and MSE_cv folds
    MSE_train = np.mean(mse_train_klist)
    MSE_cv = np.mean(mse_cv_klist)
    MSE_train_list.append(MSE_train)
    MSE_cv_list.append(MSE_cv)

    # Std of MSE's
    MSE_train_std = np.std(mse_train_klist)
    MSE_cv_std = np.std(mse_train_klist)

    print('\nAlpha:', alpha)
    print('=========================')
    print('MSE_train: %.6f, MSE_train_std: %.4f' % (MSE_train, MSE_train_std))
    print('MSE_cv: %.6f, MSE_cv_std: %.4f' % (MSE_cv,  MSE_cv_std))

# Plot results
plt.plot(alpha_list, MSE_train_list, label='Train')
plt.plot(alpha_list, MSE_cv_list, label='Validation')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel('Alpha')
plt.xticks(alpha_list, rotation=90)
plt.ylabel('MSE')
plt.title('Lineal Regression Model: Regularization parameter')

4.2 Apply the model

We train a linear regression model using the train set and the parameters tuned before, and apply this model to the test set.

To do so, we need to ordinal encode the categorical data, add polynomial features and perform feature scaling.

In[56]:
# Ordinal encoding
df_test_enc = df_test.copy()
# oe = OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['NA','Po','Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['Po','Fa','TA', 'Gd', 'Ex'], ['NA', 'Unf', 'RFn', 'Fin']])
df_test_enc[['ExterQual', 'BsmtQual', 'KitchenQual', 'GarageFinish']] = oe.transform(df_test_enc[['ExterQual', 'BsmtQual', 'KitchenQual', 'GarageFinish']])

degree = 2
alpha = 0.01
# Add polinomial features
poly= PolynomialFeatures(degree, include_bias=False)
X_mapped = poly.fit_transform(X)
test_mapped = poly.fit_transform(df_test_enc)

# Feature scaling
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_mapped_sc = scaler.fit_transform(X_mapped)
test_mapped_sc = scaler.transform(test_mapped) 

# Apply the model
model = Ridge(alpha=alpha).fit(X_mapped_sc, y)
model_prediction = model.predict(test_mapped_sc)
